# Using app in virtual environnemt

```
install de virtual environment package * python -m pip install virtualenv *

Create a virtual environment name venv * python -m venv venv *

Switch to the virtual environment in /venv/Scripts and active it * venv/Scripts/activate *

Install the flask package * pip install flask *

Run the api using * python app.py *

Generate the new requirements file corresponding to your api working * pip freeze > requirements.txt *

```

## Dockize and compile

```
consult the Dockerfile

this api use the image base * python:3.11-alpine * for it is small size, secure and digest. You can use all latest version alpine after 3.11.

`Create the docker WORKDIR called app
`copy the requirement.txt in current directory to the docker directory
`Update and install the virtual environment, then install pip
RUN apk update && apk add --no-cache \
    python3-dev \
    gcc \
    musl-dev \
    libffi-dev \
    openssl-dev \
    && python3 -m venv /venv \
    && /venv/bin/pip install --upgrade pip

`install the dependencies
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt

copy all to the docker directory
COPY . .

`chose the port
EXPOSE 5000

`run command
CMD ["python3", "app.py"]

```

```
compile the project * docker build -t flask-rest-api . *

check if the image on the project is created * docker images *

```

### Run the project

```
Be sure that any application is not current start on the same port

run the projet on server port 5000 and app port 5000 * docker run -d -p 5000:5000 flask-rest-api *

check the status of the images stated in your docker * docker ps *

```

#### igonre files

```
consult the .dockerignore

for share the project, these files and folders are igonre

Lib
Include
pyvenv.cfg
activate.fish

```

##### Start

```
This application start successfully without errors and :
- Respond to HTTP requests on port 5000
- Serve the home page at `http://localhost:5000/`
- Provide API endpoints at `http://localhost:5000/api/v1/books/`

```

